[[File:U'u, Akau Too - Marquesas.jpg|thumb|upright|Wood carvings]]
[[File:Tiki-Musée d'histoire naturelle et d'ethnographie de Colmar.jpg|thumb|upright|''Tiki'']]
'''Wood carving in the [[Marquesas Islands]]''' is a practice undertaken by many of the local master craftsmen, who are known as ''tuhuna''. The ''tuhuna'' are not only adept at wood carving, but are also skilled at tattoo art and adze manufacture.<ref name="PeregrineEmber2001">{{cite book|last1=Peregrine|first1=Peter N.|last2=Ember|first2=Melvin|title=Encyclopedia of Prehistory: Volume 3: East Asia and Oceania|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xu_Q0WGdw7YC&pg=PA247|date=31 January 2001|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-0-306-46257-3|page=247}}</ref> Marquesan wooden crafts are considered among the finest in [[French Polynesia]]; they are highly sought after,<ref>{{cite book|title=Pacific Magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aqm6AAAAIAAJ|year=2005|publisher=PacificBasin Communications|page=52}}</ref> and of consistently high quality,<ref name="Brillat1999">{{cite book|last=Brillat|first=Michael|title=South Pacific Islands|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z-TZYTj3rSkC&pg=PA208|year=1999|publisher=Nelles|isbn=978-3-88618-104-9|page=208}}</ref> although weaving, basket-making, and [[pareu painting]] is more popular, especially among women artisans.<ref name="Stanley2011">{{cite book|last=Stanley|first=David|title=Moon Tahiti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qKh44TL5dbMC&pg=PT426|date=5 April 2011|publisher=Avalon Travel|isbn=1-61238-114-6|page=426}}</ref> [[Paul Gauguin]] noted the artistic sense of decoration of the Marquesas and appreciated the "unheard of sense of decoration" in their creative art forms.{{Sfn|Kjellgren|Ivory|2005|p=3}}

==History==
Wooden figures from Marquesan prehistory can reveal much about the early practices of the local peoples. The popularity of Marquesaan wood carving was due to its increasing demand in foreign countries. This was also a consequence of the introduction of imported metal carving tools in the late 19th century.{{Sfn|Kjellgren|Ivory|2005|p=4}} As a result, new styles emerged in wood carving such as decorating the full surface of an artifact with low-relief designs which had similarities to tattoo designs. This was done to meet the growing demand for souvenirs in the late 19th century.{{Sfn|Kjellgren|Ivory|2005|p=35}}

==Wood cultivation==
Material used to make artifacts includes [[Oceania rosewood]] (''Miro'' or ''Mi'o''), [[oceania walnut]] (''tou''), [[iron wood]] (''aito''), the [[coconut tree]] (''tumu ha'ari'' or ''tumu'ehi'') as well as Pacific rosewood (''[[Thespesia populnea]]'') and ''temana'' (''[[Calophyllum inophyllum]]''); iron wood (''[[Casuarina equisetifolia]]'') is used to carve war clubs and other artifacts.<ref name="Hinanui">{{cite web|url=http://www.hinanui-artpolynesien.com/en/content/8-marquesan-handicraft|title=Marquesan Handicraft|publisher=Hinanui-artpolynesien.com|accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref>{{Sfn|Kjellgren|Ivory|2005|p=116}} Sandalwood was cleared out of the Marquesas between 1814 and 1817.{{sfn|Dodge|1976|p=60}} It is important to the Marquesan people to use wood from the islands, because of its quality and it follows the tradition of their ancestors. Typically, the wood is dried for up for 10 years, and then treated against pests. While some craftsmen cultivate trees in their own gardens for their wood products, they also purchase it from vendors who grow it in the valleys.<ref name="Hinanui"/>

==Products==
[[File:Artisanat marquisien.JPG|thumb|A display of wood carvings]]
In 1961, the ''Anthropological Papers'' of the [[American Museum of Natural History]] documented that "the number of Historic period wooden figures collected in the Marquesas attests to the amount of wood carving for monumental purposes".<ref>{{cite book|title=Anthropological Papers of the American Museum of Natural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Jm0LAAAAIAAJ|year=1961|publisher=American Museum of Natural History|page=155}}</ref> [[Ua Huka]] is particularly well known in the area for its wood carvings. Common objects include sculptural representations of [[Polynesian mythology|Polynesian gods]], humans and animals, and utilitarian items such as decorated bowls, paddles, and clubs.{{sfn|Handy|1922|p=19}} [[Toewood]] and [[rosewood]] are featured in the wood carvings from [[Nuku Hiva]], with bowls and spears made from the former, while tables and chessboards are carved from the latter.{{sfn|Cruising World|1989|p=20}} The ''[[tiki]]'' figurine, "an anthropomorphic figure portrayed with huge oval eyes, arching brows and open  mouth", is typical of the Marquesan arts.<ref name="PeregrineEmber2001"/> Though tikis are most common as stone statues, they are also familiar motifs in wood carving and tattoos in the islands. Patterns used for both wood carving and body decorating have been noted, such as the ''honu kea'' ([[woodlouse]]), ''mata hoata'' (brilliant eye), ''ka'ake'' ([[underarm]] curve), ''poka'a'' ([[wood block]]), and ''enata'' (man).{{sfn|Handy|1922|p=19}}

